#263 Misc
    :date: 2026-04-20 21:45
    :shortdes: Traffic Control Hall of Shame: just, except bicycles
    :tags: Design | Minneapolis | Nonsense

.I recently wrote about <a href="#post-258">the most confusing</a> EXCEPT
BICYCLES sign I had ever seen. But you can't beat this new one on the Bryant
Ave bikeway northbound for pure zaniness:

<img class="center" width="500px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/except-bicycles-only.jpg">

.And this isn't a one-off: these are posted <em>repeatedly</em> all along the
length of the off-street section between Lake Street and 50th Street.

.In context, obviously what is meant here is “one way, do not enter, except of
course bicycles because the bike path is two-way, as you can see.” So the other
one keeps its crown for “most confusing,” since I still don't know what it
means. But did the Minneapolis Street Department run out of budget for DO NOT
ENTER signs? And from a safety perspective, if I had to choose whether to put
up the DO NOT ENTER sign or the EXCEPT BICYCLES sign, I know which one I'd
pick, and it sure isn't the one they did.


#262 Misc
    :date: 2026-04-20 19:30
    :shortdes: The future of urban transportation is here and it is e-bikes
    :tags: Society | Tech

.Maybe I should shut up <a href="#post-252">about</a> <a
href="#post-253">e-bikes</a>, but I find it remarkable that 6 months after
getting mine, I <em>still</em> get this weird feeling every time I get on it:
this feels like a device that belongs decades in the future, after we get
everything figured out, but here it is and I get to use it now!

.For anyone who hasn't used an electric vehicle of some kind, it is a strange
experience the first time you realize that you're essentially sitting on or in
a smartphone with a motor and some wheels. It has a little battery indicator
that looks just like the one on your standard electronic device, and a screen,
and a computer, and a lithium-ion battery. It barely makes any noise, has no
exhaust, and costs almost nothing to run – just flip the switch and go, and
when you get home plug it into the wall so it's ready for tomorrow.

.Compared to driving, riding my e-bike is easier, cheaper, more fun, better for
my mental and physical health (and this is not a subtle effect – I am
consciously aware of feeling better on days when I ride my bike, and feeling
blah when I decide to drive and get in my car), better for the environment, and
better for the urban fabric and other people's health. Compared to riding
public transit, it's more flexible and usually faster (even on routes that
cross the whole city, and this is often true even in places with fantastic
transit). There are still times when driving my car makes sense, but over the
last couple of months my default mode of transportation for trips up to 8 miles
one-way has become my e-bike, because it is usually the most convenient and
pleasant option. I need a good reason to choose something else.

.So my unsolicited advice is, if you live in a city and you've never ridden an
e-bike, even if you don't think you need or want one, see if you can borrow one
and try it out for half an hour, because you might change your mind, and if you
do I can almost guarantee your life will be better. And if you've thought about
it but you're on the fence, you should go buy one yesterday. I am angry that I
waited so long.


#261 Misc
    :date: 2026-04-20 18:20
    :shortdes: This is why people think AI is so much worse than it is
    :tags: AI | Society

.I try to keep up with the latest news on AI of all kinds (which is like
drinking from a fire hose that's spewing a liquid that makes you worried the
world is going to end, but also seems pretty important for that reason, plus
it's quite relevant to my job and my daily life right now). One thing that
people keep mentioning is that if you haven't tried the latest pro models
available with a cheap monthly subscription, and instead you're using free
ChatGPT or the AI answers at the top of Google, you're using AI that is months
behind, which is an <em>eternity</em> right now, and you likely have no clue
what it's actually capable of.

.I've been a happy Claude Max subscriber for many months now, pretty much
exclusively using <a href="https://claude.ai">claude.ai</a> and Claude Code
except for a few very specific uses, so I haven't witnessed this effect
firsthand for the most part. Today, out of laziness, I typed in a simple
question I had into my search engine, <a href="https://kagi.com">Kagi</a>,
triggering its “quick answer” feature, rather than entering it on claude.ai
like I normally do – and I was stunned by how useless the result was.

.Here's the result I got from “Quick Answer”:
<img class="center" width="695px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/quick-answers-kagi.png">

.The free “quick answer” tool gives a list of slop that does absolutely nothing
to address my problem. It didn't even understand my question – it replaced the
preposition <em>in</em> in my question with <em>from</em>, not understanding
that I wanted queries issued while editing a particular repository to use a
particular skill, rather than wanting to make a skill that was in a repository
available everywhere. And the summary at the bottom basically tells me that
skills exist and one can use them, which is ridiculous since asking the
question I did already implies that I know this!

.I could probably click on some of the references and eventually find an
answer. But if I wanted to look at a bunch of documentation and crappy web
pages, I would just search Google and click the links; there's no reason to ask
an LLM this question if I'm going to have to go read web pages anyway.

.Now here's the result from Opus 4.7 (the latest Claude model, available
starting from $20 a month), on the exact same query:
<img class="center" width="695px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/quick-answers-claude.png">

.It turns out that you can't in fact do quite what I had wanted to do.
But this answer understands exactly what I'm asking and explains that it's not
possible, and also gives me multiple very usable workarounds that I can choose
from, along with an understanding of how the whole skill-loading framework
works that will help me to understand and troubleshoot why my skill often isn't
being loaded when it would be useful, if the workarounds don't work or aren't
acceptable. It's also written at the right level for my knowledge on the topic
(and it got this bang-on despite having memory off and my prompt being only one
sentence!). It's in a format that sounds more or less like something a normal
person would write, rather than an annoying list of content-free bullet points.
And it gives one useful reference link rather than a gazillion of them.

.The answer isn't perfect – it has a couple of minor errors (like saying
“combining 1 and 2”, but the thing it's referencing as “1” isn't the thing that
has a number 1 next to it), and I could definitely write a clearer version –
but, very unlike the “Quick Answer” slop version, it gave me exactly the
information I needed to solve my problem without needing to think hard or look
up anything else. And I gave it a frankly awful prompt out of laziness; among
other things, I didn't explain what problem I was actually having (making the
conversation subject to the <a href="https://xyproblem.info/">XY problem</a>),
and as it pointed out I didn't clarify what “force” meant to me or what would
count as a solution. I expect I could get an even better result if I gave it
more context.

.I have to admit now that this example might be slightly cheating because
Claude has a special “Claude help guide” function built in, so it probably
knows a bit more about Claude skills than about an average tool. But I didn't
intentionally cherry-pick this one, and the quality is not an outlier – I get
responses of a similar quality for almost all questions I ask Claude.

.All in all, right now, if you've only tried free AI, or, worse, only the AI
that's at the top of search engines and in customer-service chats, you simply
can't have an informed opinion on what AI (as a whole technology ecosystem) can
do or whether it is useful. It would be like saying that you don't enjoy
looking at paintings, when you've only ever seen finger-paintings that someone
else's preschooler made.


#260 Misc
    :date: 2026-04-15 20:35
    :shortdes: Forgetting anniversaries
    :tags: Society

.Here's something about the world I legitimately don't understand: what is up with the trope of people (especially straight men) forgetting each other's anniversaries?

.I'm an anniversaries person; it's a way that I like interacting with my history. I very frequently remember most meaningful dates organically, either on the day, or the day before or after or something, and I keep a calendar of them. But if my romantic partner was not that kind of person, it would not bother me in the slightest if I was the one reminding them every time. If we wanted to do something on that date where both of us needed to be on board earlier, we'd plan it ahead of time, because obviously that's what you do.

.OK, but maybe I'm just unusual, and for many people it really does make them feel unloved if their partner “forgets their anniversary” (which I'm putting in quotes because this conventional phrasing makes “remembering” it at a specific moment normative and I'm not convinced that's right). They don't decouple love from the person not being particularly attentive to time in this particular way. I can believe that, and it doesn't seem especially unreasonable. So then, if your partner is actually bothered by you forgetting an anniversary and you nevertheless keep forgetting it…there's this really cool app called “Calendar” – maybe you've heard of it – that can remind you of things that happen on specific dates. How is this a hard problem to solve?!

.Or is it that people actually don't care, but they're just playfully antagonistic about this thing in particular all the time? This is surely true for some people, but it also seems to me like many people are legitimately put out by it.


#259 Misc
    :date: 2026-03-20 08:45
    :shortdes: Branches of math might be useless because you don't know them well enough to notice they're useful
    :tags: Math | Society

.Sometimes people say things like “X branch of math I learned in school is
never useful!”

.While I will happily concede that some math classes are more practically
useful to most people than others, I think the math you feel comfortable with
creates a selection effect that makes this hard to judge: if you don't really
grok that kind of math (or math in general, for that matter), you're unlikely
to see opportunities to use it.

.Personally, I have often griped that calculus is cool but rarely useful
outside of very specific fields or professions. But this morning I was
realizing I've had several moments lately where calculus probably would have
helped me answer a question I had, but I just shrugged it off and found an
answer a different way, or didn't find an answer at all because it wasn't that
important to me. Calculus made sense to me when I took it, and I still
understand the overarching insights and principles – limits, derivatives,
integrals, etc. – but I haven't done any calculus <em>problems</em> for
14 years, so I remember little about how to actually manipulate them, and would
have to sit and think very hard and probably consult a textbook or LLM to
figure out how to apply the tools to a moderately complicated problem. That
means I just don't take it that seriously as an option.

.Meanwhile, many people claim to me that algebra and geometry aren't very
useful, but I use them all the time; and I use them in everyday life, not in
some obscure professional way, so I don't think it's that my opportunity to use
them differs dramatically from other people's. Instead, I imagine the
discrepancy is that I have a full enough intuitive understanding of them that
it's very obvious when I'm seeing an algebra-shaped problem, and I know how to
formulate and solve the problem if I want to.

.This is an instance of a general pattern in which the world looks different
when you have a full understanding of something. E.g., if you study typography,
suddenly you will notice all sorts of micro-design choices and errors, or if
you study mushrooms, suddenly you'll notice mushrooms everywhere in nature that
you never saw before even though they were always there.


#258 Misc
    :date: 2026-03-05 23:30
    :shortdes: Traffic Control Hall of Shame: these lanes, except bicycles
    :tags: Design | Minneapolis | Nonsense

.I find that EXCEPT BICYCLES signs are often used in confusing ways, but this
one, newly installed on Hennepin Avenue southbound just before its intersection
with 24th Street, might be the worst one I've ever seen:

<img class="center" width="500px" loading="lazy" src="assets/images/except-bicycles.jpg">

.First of all, note that there is a two-way bicycle path at the sidewalk level
on the other side of the street from where this picture was taken, about 60
feet across the wide avenue from the sign. So if you're riding a bicycle in the
bicycle lane, as one typically does, you probably can't even <em>see</em> this
sign, even if you for some reason were to look across four lanes of traffic at
the opposite side of the road. And if, after all that, you looked at it and saw
it, you presumably wouldn't need to be told that the markings painted in the
car lanes didn't apply to you in the off-street bicycle lanes. Nor can I see
any way a motorist would find this sign enlightening.

.OK, so let's give this the benefit of the doubt and suppose it applies
specifically to cyclists riding in the car lanes on a street with a two-way
protected bicycle path. This would be a slightly unusual but perfectly legal
and not completely ridiculous thing to do; perhaps you're only going a block
south and it isn't worth waiting for the light and crossing the street to the
path on the other side. So then what? What does this even mean? If you're on a
bike in the car lane, lanes don't apply? You can YOLO a right turn from the
left turn lane? You can only make a U-turn?

.My best guess is that they're trying to convey that if you're on a bike in the
car lane, it's legal to go straight from the right turn lane into the bus lane
on the other side of the intersection. But I have no idea if that's actually
it. And even if that is it, I'd be surprised if more than 5% of people work
that out from the signage the first time they see it. It doesn't actually say
that, in any way whatsoever.

.(Also, the legality of riding a bike in the bus lane in Minneapolis in the
first place is unclear to me. It's not mentioned as either legal or illegal on
any signage I've ever seen; I see people do it sometimes, and have done so
myself occasionally, but only if there are no buses nearby.)


#257 Misc
    :date: 2026-03-05 13:15
    :shortdes: Tailscale
    :tags: Tech

.(<em>If you don't know anything about networking, use multiple computers on a
daily basis, write code, run servers, etc., this will be uninteresting. If you
do, and you haven't heard of Tailscale, this might be one of the most useful
things you've read in a while!</em>)

.<a href="https://tailscale.com/">Tailscale</a> has been a thing for a few
years now, but I never quite took the time to look into it and understand what
it did. Recently, Claude recommended it to me to solve a specific problem, and
having started using it, I am upset I waited this long – it's been a huge
quality-of-life improvement!

.Basically, Tailscale allows you to set up – for free, for up to 3 users, and
for a very reasonable price if you need more complex security and identity
management – a virtual local network that can be composed of, essentially, any
devices connected to the internet, anywhere. You install one piece of software
and log in on each device, and…that's it. I can access my desktop computer or
my file server network from a coffee shop halfway across the world. Or for that
matter, access my laptop on mobile hotspot from my desktop! No NAT
configuration, no dynamic DNS, no SSH tunneling, no extra public server, no
attack surface created by punching holes in a firewall, it just magically
works. You can directly connect to things when you're off-LAN using the same
IPs you would use on the LAN (and there are other routing and hostname options
too if you need them).

.You can also configure most devices as “exit nodes” and allow internet traffic
to be bounced through them from any other device, if you need to get around
geolocation blocks that require you to be “at home” or you're on a sketchy
network and want an extra layer of protection.

.It took me a couple of hours to get my network set up, but almost all of that
time was spent getting the unsupported configuration of Tailscale on a FreeBSD
NAS serving files via NFS working. If your network configuration is even
slightly more normal than mine, it would probably take you all of 20 minutes to
get everything working.

.If you have a hacky system for doing any of this, or if you don't have the
ability to use your home devices when you're away from home because it feels
like too much work to set up, check it out.


